properties.Name: Ntabankulu Local Municipality
properties.detail: Ntabankulu Local Municipality is a local municipality in Alfred Nzo District Municipality in the Wild Coast Region of the Eastern Cape Province in South Africa.

properties.Name: Mbizana Local Municipality
properties.detail: Mbizana Local Municipality, situated in the Eastern Cape Province along the R61 road connecting KwaZulu-Natal’s South Coast to the N2 highway, includes a main town and surrounding villages. Covering an area of approximately 2,806 km², it has a population of about 246,516 people living in 46,730 households. The municipality is culturally diverse, home to tribes such as the Xhosa, Mpondo, Sotho, and Nguni, with the Mpondo tribe—whose unique dialect, isiMpondo, blends isiXhosa and isiZulu—being the majority. With women constituting 54% of the population, Mbizana promotes their active involvement in key decision-making roles within municipal institutions to reflect this demographic reality.

properties.Name: Umzimvubu Local Municipality
properties.detail: Umzimvubu Local Municipality, situated within the Alfred Nzo District of the Eastern Cape Province, covers an area of 2,506 km². A 2009 study by the Alfred Nzo District Municipality reported 59,924 households in the area. Predominantly rural, most of the population resides in dispersed, low-density traditional settlements, except in the two urban centers of Mount Ayliff and Mount Frere.

properties.Name: Matatiele Local Municipality
properties.detail: Matatiele Local Municipality (MLM) is located within the Alfred Nzo District Municipality. It is bordered to the north by Lesotho, to the northeast by KwaZulu-Natal (KZN), and to the southwest by Elundini Municipality. Covering an area of 4,352 km², MLM accounts for 58% of the Alfred Nzo District's total geographical area.

properties.Name: Dr Pixley Ka Isaka Seme Local Municipality
King Sabata Dalindyebo Local Municipality
properties.detail: King Sabata Dalindyebo Local Municipality (KSD LM) is a Category B municipality located within the OR Tambo District Municipality in the Eastern Cape Province of South Africa. Covering an area of 3,027 km², it is the largest of the five municipalities in the district, accounting for approximately 25% of the district’s geographical area.

properties.Name: Mhlontlo Local Municipality
properties.detail: Mhlontlo Local Municipality is a Category B4 rural municipality encompassing the towns of Qumbu and Tsolo. It is located in the northeastern part of the Eastern Cape Province, along the N2 route between Mthatha and Mt. Frere, and the R396 between Tsolo and Maclear. The municipality covers an area of 2,614 km², with a population density of 73.3 people per km².

properties.Name: Nyandeni Local Municipality
properties.detail: Nyandeni Local Municipality is a Category B municipality located within the OR Tambo District in the Eastern Cape Province. It lies approximately 30 km south of Mthatha and 50 km north of Port St Johns. The municipality is bordered by Mhlontlo to the north, King Sabata Dalindyebo to the west, Port St Johns to the east, and the Indian Ocean to the south. Its eastern boundary includes a 20 km stretch of coastline, while the Umzimvubu River forms part of its western edge.

properties.Name: Port St Johns Local Municipality
properties.detail: Port St. Johns Local Municipality is a Category B municipality in the OR Tambo District of the Eastern Cape Province, South Africa. It is named after its main town, Port St. Johns, which is located along the Wild Coast—an area known for its scenic, rugged coastline stretching approximately 270 km.

properties.Name: Ingquza Hill Local Municipality
properties.detail: Ingquza Hill Local Municipality, previously called Qaukeni Local Municipality, is a Category B municipality located within the OR Tambo District in the Eastern Cape Province of South Africa. The name change reflects efforts to align municipal identities with local heritage.

properties.Name: Walter Sisulu Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Walter Sisulu Local Municipality is a Category B municipality in the western part of the Joe Gqabi District, Eastern Cape. Located south of the Orange River and Gariep Dam, it borders both the Northern Cape and Free State provinces. It is the largest municipality in the district, covering half of its area, and was formed in 2016 through the merger of the Gariep and Maletswai municipalities.
The region features mountainous terrain, hills, and valleys, with diverse vegetation that includes the nationally significant Eastern Mixed Nama Karoo biome. The local economy is largely driven by stock farming, particularly sheep farming, and the area's rivers and streams are known for trout fishing.

properties.Name: Senqu Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Senqu Local Municipality is a Category B municipality located in the Joe Gqabi District of the Eastern Cape Province. It borders Lesotho to the north, Chris Hani District to the south, Elundini to the east, and Walter Sisulu to the west. Covering a third of the district’s geographical area, it is one of three municipalities in the district.
Senqu was formed through the amalgamation of the former municipalities of Lady Grey, Barkly East, Sterkspruit, Rossouw, and Rhodes, reflecting a history of regional integration.

properties.Name: Elundini Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Elundini Local Municipality (ELM) is a Category B municipality in the north-eastern part of the Eastern Cape, within the Joe Gqabi District. It borders Alfred Nzo District to the north, Chris Hani to the south, OR Tambo to the east, and Lesotho and Senqu to the west. It is the smallest of the three municipalities in the district, comprising about 25% of its geographical area.
Elundini is known for its scenic landscapes, fertile soils, and high rainfall, offering strong potential for economic growth and improved living standards. Employment is mainly found in urban areas and commercial farming, with agriculture, commercial, and service sectors being key employers. Rural areas suffer from low employment due to weak economic foundations and a reliance on subsistence activities with minimal surplus for trade.

properties.Name: Emalahleni Local Municipality
properties.detail: Emalahleni Local Municipality is a Category B municipality located within the Chris Hani District in the Eastern Cape province. It consists of 17 wards that serve three main towns: Lady Frere (home to the main municipal offices), Indwe, and Dordrecht. While Indwe and Dordrecht are largely urban and include farms, Lady Frere also serves surrounding villages.

properties.Name: Intsika Yethu Local Municipality
properties.detail: Intsika Yethu Municipality is made up of 21 wards, 2 towns (Cofimvaba and Tsomo), and 214 villages. The majority of the population resides in rural villages scattered throughout the area. The municipality prides itself on having some of the best agricultural resources in the country, supported by three major irrigation schemes: Ncora, Qamata, and Bilatye. The R61 national road passes through the municipality, linking it to the O.R. Tambo and Amathole District Municipalities.

properties.Name: Inxuba Yethemba Local Municipality
properties.detail: The Inxuba Yethemba Local Municipality is a Category B municipality located within the Chris Hani District in the Eastern Cape Province, approximately 240 km north of the Nelson Mandela Metropolitan Municipality. It is one of six municipalities in the district and covers about one-third of its geographical area. Cradock includes the Cradock suburb, as well as the Lingelihle and Michausdal communities. Middelburg consists of the Middelburg suburb, along with the Kwanonzame, Lusaka, and Midros communities.

properties.Name: Enoch Mgijima Local Municipality
properties.detail: Enoch Mgijima Local Municipality is situated within the Chris Hani District in the Eastern Cape province of South Africa. It was established following the August 2016 local government elections through the amalgamation of the former Tsolwana, Inkwanca, and Lukhanji municipalities.

properties.Name: Sakhisizwe Local Municipality
properties.detail: Sakhisizwe Local Municipality is a Category B4 municipality (primarily rural, with 61% rural population) located in the Chris Hani District of the Eastern Cape Province. It spans 2,355 km² and comprises the main towns of Cala—where the administrative offices are based—and Khowa, along with surrounding rural villages and farms. As the smallest of the six municipalities in the district, it accounts for only 6% of the district's geographical area. It is bordered by the Joe Gqabi District to the north, Intsika Yethu to the south, Engcobo to the east, and Emalahleni to the west.

properties.Name: Engcobo Local Municipality
properties.detail: Dr AB Xuma Local Municipality, formerly known as Engcobo Municipality, is a local municipality situated within the Chris Hani District in the Eastern Cape province of South Africa. The name change reflects a move to honour Dr Alfred Bitini Xuma, a prominent South African medical doctor and political leader.

properties.Name: Amahlathi Local Municipality
properties.detail: Amahlathi Local Municipality is a Category B municipality located within the Amathole District in the Eastern Cape Province. It is bordered by Chris Hani District (north), Buffalo City Metro (south), Mnquma and Great Kei (east), and Raymond Mhlaba (west). As one of six municipalities in the district, it serves as an administrative area within the region.

properties.Name: Great Kei Local Municipality
properties.detail: Great Kei Local Municipality is a Category B municipality within the Amathole District in the Eastern Cape Province. It is situated near the former industrial towns of Butterworth, Qonce (King William’s Town), and East London. Bordered by Stutterheim to the north, the Wild Coast to the southeast, the Great Kei River to the east, and Buffalo City to the west, it is the smallest of the six municipalities in the district.

properties.Name: Mnquma Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Mnquma Local Municipality is a Category B municipality in the south-eastern part of the Eastern Cape, under the Amathole District Municipality. It was formed by merging the former Butterworth, Ngqamakhwe, and Centane Transitional Regional Councils.
Mnquma borders three other local municipalities, the Chris Hani District, and the Indian Ocean. It is one of six municipalities within the Amathole District.

properties.Name: Mbhashe Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Mbhashe Local Municipality is a Category B municipality located in the south-eastern part of the Eastern Cape, within the Amathole District. It is coastal, stretching along the Indian Ocean from the Mncwasa River in the north to the Qhora River in the south.
The municipality shares borders with King Sabata Dalindyebo (north-east), Mnquma (south), Ntsika Yethu (south-west), and Ngcobo (west).

properties.Name: Raymond Mhlaba Local Municipality
properties.detail:
The Municipality is named after anti apartheid stalwart, Raymond Mhlaba Local Municipality, often called "Oom Ray," is a rural municipality in the Eastern Cape formed through the 2016 amalgamation of the former Nkonkobe and Nxuba municipalities. Major towns include Alice, Fort Beaufort, Adelaide, Bedford, Middledrift, Hogsback, and Seymour. The municipality lies along the historic Winterberg mountain range (intaba zeNkonkobe), where key resistance battles—like the War of the Axe and War of Maqoma—took place.
The local economy is predominantly agricultural, driven by citrus farming, forestry, and crop production. Citrus is one of the largest employment sectors, alongside timber processing. While the area is rich in cultural heritage and natural beauty, its tourism sector remains underdeveloped. Important but underutilised heritage institutions include Lovedale College, Healdtown, and the University of Fort Hare. Natural assets like the Amathole Mountains also hold untapped tourism potential.

properties.Name: Ngqushwa Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Ngqushwa Local Municipality is a Category B municipality within the Amathole District in the Eastern Cape Province. It is predominantly rural and accounts for 10% of the district's geographical area, making it one of the smaller municipalities in the district.
The municipality is bordered by the Keiskamma River to the east, the Great Fish River to the west, and the Indian Ocean to the south.

properties.Name: Dr Nkosazana Dlamini Zuma Local Municipality
Blue Crane Route Local Municipality
properties.detail: Blue Crane Route Local Municipality is a Category B municipality in the Sarah Baartman District Municipality of the Eastern Cape Province. Named after South Africa’s national bird, the Blue Crane, it is the second largest of seven municipalities in the district, accounting for 19% of the district’s geographical area. The municipality covers approximately 11,068 km² and has a population of nearly 40,000 people living in the three towns of Cookhouse, Pearston, and Somerset East. Somerset East, situated at the foot of the Boschberg Mountains, serves as the administrative center of the municipality.

properties.Name: Dr Beyers Naude Local Municipality
properties.detail: Dr Beyers Naudé Local Municipality is the third-largest local municipality in South Africa by area, covering approximately 28,690 km². It is located in the Karoo region and includes towns such as Graaff-Reinet, Willowmore, Aberdeen, Jansenville, Steytlerville, Nieu-Bethesda, Klipplaat, and Rietbron, along with various smaller settlements and farms. The municipality is known for its natural beauty, rich heritage, diverse cultures, and appealing climate, making it a notable tourist destination. Graaff-Reinet, the fourth-oldest town in South Africa and known as the “Gem of the Karoo,” serves as the political and administrative centre and is the main hub for agri-tourism and population concentration.

properties.Name: Kou-Kamma Local Municipality
properties.detail:
KouKamma Local Municipality spans 3,575 km² and features diverse geography, including a rugged coastline, coastal plains, and mountain ranges such as the Kouga and Tsitsikamma. Its western boundary is marked by the Bloukrans River, which separates it from the Western Cape. Known for its scenic landscapes and low population density, the municipality has no large towns, only small villages and hamlets spread across 6 electoral wards and governed by a 12-member council.
The coastal region, Tsitsikamma, is notable for dairy farming, forestry, and tourism, including attractions like the Storms River Mouth in the Garden Route National Park. Inland lies the Langkloof Valley, a fertile region for deciduous fruit farming, separated from the coast by the Tsitsikamma Mountains and bordered to the north by the Kouga Mountains.

properties.Name: Kouga Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Kouga Local Municipality (KLM) is located in the Sarah Baartman District of the Eastern Cape, west of Nelson Mandela Bay, covering 2,419 km². It comprises nine towns—Jeffreys Bay, Humansdorp, St Francis Bay, Cape St Francis, Oyster Bay, Hankey, Patensie, Loerie, and Thornhill—along with smaller settlements and agricultural areas.
As of the 2022 Census, Kouga has an estimated population of 107,014. Afrikaans is the most spoken language (58.4%), followed by isiXhosa (29.9%) and English (6.1%).
Traditionally reliant on tourism and agriculture, Kouga is now emerging as a key renewable energy hub in South Africa. Several wind farms are operational, and additional renewable energy projects—such as solar and biomass—are in development.

properties.Name: Sundays River Valley Local Municipality
properties.detail: Sundays River Valley Municipality is located in the Sarah Baartman District of the Eastern Cape, South Africa, with a population of approximately 70,000. It is a major citrus-producing region in the country and includes significant conservation areas such as the Addo Elephant National Park.

properties.Name: Ndlambe Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Ndlambe Local Municipality is a Category B municipality within the Sarah Baartman District in the Eastern Cape. Bordered by Makana, Ngqushwa, Sundays River Valley, and the Atlantic Ocean, it is the smallest of the seven municipalities in the district, covering just 3% of its total area.
Located in the Eastern Coastal Zone, Ndlambe is known for its unspoiled coastline, well-preserved river mouths, intertidal areas, and diverse vegetation. The area has low-density coastal development and significant tourism potential.

properties.Name: Makana Local Municipality
properties.detail:
Makana Local Municipality is a Category B municipality in the western part of the Eastern Cape, within the Sarah Baartman District. It lies strategically between Gqeberha (120 km west) and East London (180 km east), both major industrial hubs with container ports and airports.
The area is renowned for conservation, with nearly a million hectares dedicated to game reserves, including well-known sites such as Shamwari, Double Drift, and Kwandwe. Makhanda (formerly Grahamstown) is the municipal centre and cultural heart, home to over 70 declared National Heritage Sites.
